ct with supporters, the role of group portraiture, and representations of Victorian MPs. The final part of the book examines how major politicians, including Palmerston, Gladstone and Disraeli, interacted with mass commercial imagery. The book will appeal to a broad range of scholars and students across political, social and cultural history, art history and visual studies, cultural and media studies and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtxPolitical aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aArt; Political aspects; Great Britain; History, 19th century. 0aCaricatures and cartoonsxPolitical aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aCaricatures and cartoons; Political aspects; Great Britain; History, 19th century. 0aPortrait paintingxPolitical aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPortrait painting; Political aspects; Great Britain; History, 19th century. 0aVisual communication in artzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aVisual communication in art; Great Britain; History, 19th century. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aConservative identities.  aLord Derby.  aLord John Russell.  aReformer identities.  acartoons.  aelectoral politics.  amemorials.  apictorial press.  apolitical culture.  apolitical likenesses.  apolitical portraits.  aportrait prints.  aportrait testimonials.  apublic opinion.  areform bills.  arepresentative system.  astatues.  avisual culture.  avisual politics.1 aMiller, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2015 eBook-Packagez978311128311140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526111715423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526111715/original  a978-3-11-128311-1  Man